 Braudy's argument for the subject of nature as a genre. Also included are essays on melodrama, race, film noir, and the industrial context of genre production. The contributors confront the poststructuralist critique of genre head-on; together they are certain to shape future debates concerning the viability and vitality of genre in studying American cinema.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aFilm. 4aGeneral. 4aPerforming Arts. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh1 aAltman, Rick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBraudy, Leo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrowne, Nick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrowne, Nick, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aClover, Carol J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLipsitz, George, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRogin, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRussell, David J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchatz, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSobchacic, Vivian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilliams, Linda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052020731840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052091855940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520918559423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520918559/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_UCA_YUP